Lindroth, 1953b: 174. Type locality: &quot;Cheticamp, Nova Scotia&quot; (holotype label). Holotype (â™‚) in CNC [# 6574]. Etymology. The specific name honors the English clergyman, entomologist, and naturalist William Kirby [1759-1850] who is best known to the North American entomological community for his taxonomic treatment of the insects brought back by John Richardson from the second arctic expedition (1825-1827) of Sir John Franklin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="645" pageNumber="646" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="645" pageNumber="646">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="645" pageNumber="646">This species has a disjunct distribution. In the east, the species is found from Cape Breton Island to southeastern Manitoba south to southern Indiana, southern Pennsylvania, and New Jersey; in the west, the species ranges from southern British Columbia south to southwestern California, east to northern Idaho [see Noonan 1996: Fig. 238].</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
